<p class="eyebrow">Infrastructure</p>
<h1>Infrastructure &amp; uptime</h1>
<p class="lede">Six US POPs, redundant carrier interconnections, STIR/SHAKEN attestation, and a 99.99% voice availability target. This page details where VoiceTel runs and how it has performed.</p>

<h2>POP locations</h2>
<p>VoiceTel operates voice and SIP infrastructure in six US data centers. Each POP terminates redundant carrier interconnections and runs the VoiceML runtime locally, with cross-POP failover for in-call redundancy when configured.</p>
<ul>
	<li><strong>NYC</strong> — New York metro</li>
	<li><strong>CLT</strong> — Charlotte</li>
	<li><strong>ORD</strong> — Chicago</li>
	<li><strong>DEN</strong> — Denver</li>
	<li><strong>DFW</strong> — Dallas</li>
	<li><strong>SJC</strong> — San Jose</li>
</ul>

<h2>Carrier interconnections</h2>
<p>Multiple Tier-1 carrier hand-offs per POP for origination and termination. Routing decisions are made per-call based on least-cost and quality metrics, with automatic failover when a carrier degrades.</p>

<h2>Uptime target</h2>
<p>99.99% voice availability target measured per calendar month. This is the platform target; specific service tiers (e.g. dedicated SIP trunks, hosted PBX) may have separate SLAs documented in their service agreements.</p>

